  "prompt": "Why are Americans athletes get permission from wada to take serious doping drugs and are not disqualified?",
  "response": "The World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) does not allow athletes to take doping drugs. WADA has established strict regulations and a list of prohibited substances and methods to ensure fair competition and the health and safety of athletes. However, some athletes may receive exemptions known as Therapeutic Use Exemptions (TUEs) if they have a legitimate medical condition that requires the use of a banned substance. \n\nTo receive a TUE, an athlete must provide medical evidence that demonstrates the necessity of the prohibited substance for their health. The application is reviewed by a panel of medical experts who determine whether the exemption should be granted.\n\nIt is important to note that TUEs are granted based on medical need and strict criteria, and not all applications are approved. The process is designed to ensure that athletes are not gaining a competitive advantage by using banned substances and that the integrity of sport is maintained.\n\nIf an athlete is found to be using banned substances without an approved TUE, they would be subject to sanctions, including disqualification and other penalties as determined by WADA and the relevant sports governing bodies.",
